ith overlapping context\n- repeated fresh-session tests of the same skill\n\nAvoid hard-coding main/sidecar labels until the source data supports them. For\nnow, expose enough facts for the consuming agent to decide.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- no provider-native resume\n- no generated persistent handoff summary\n- no magic `handoff` command for v1\n- no `recap` command\n- no public `sessions`, `timeline`, or `records` drill-down flow\n- no durable inferred ownership like \"this branch belongs to this session\"\n- no GitButler app API dependency for the first flow\n- no automatic transcript dumping into `but status`\n- no product-specific review browsing payloads\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Should `skim` gain a read-layer cache if cold reads become annoying in normal\n  use?\n- Can we reliably capture provider metadata that distinguishes top-level\n  sessions from spawned subagents?\n- Should compaction/resume grouping be a later derived feature, or do we need to\n  store more source metadata now to make it possible?\n- How much transcript text should human-readable `show` expose by default?\n\n## Implementation Status\n\nThe prototype converged on `skim` plus `show`.\n\nDone:\n\n- added turn storage, read/query support, and branch/review/change lookup\n- added compact `skim`\n- changed `skim` to walk all related sessions and all turns chronologically\n- removed the old `recap` command\n- removed the public agent path for `sessions`, `timeline`, and `records`\n- kept `show` as the exact drill-down command\n- updated the Codex/Claude skill wording so agents start with `skim` and drill\n  down only when useful\n\nLeft:\n\n- keep preview/share-specific projection out of `but-agentlog`; implement it in\n  a later feature-specific layer when the review browsing service is designed\n- decide whether the first product surface needs cursor/filter support beyond\n  `skim` and bounded `show`\n- design the review web service / browsing layer before adding share-specific\n  projection c